<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06054d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06054d">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06054d"> 54(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> nose break, new face / not same</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">A cet &acirc;ge de quatre ans, o&ugrave; le prestige d&apos;ordinaire commence &agrave; se dissiper, un enfant laisse tomber sa poup&eacute;e ch&eacute;rie, qui malheureusement se casse le nez. Cris affreux, d&eacute;sespoir= terrible, qui redouble lorsqu&apos;un imprudent de p&egrave;re, ne prenant pas la chose assez au s&eacute;rieux, moiti&eacute; riant, moiti&eacute; cherchant &agrave; raccommoder le pauvre visage, enfonce le reste du nez malade dans une &eacute;norme cavit&eacute;. Alors, un chagrin m&ecirc;l&eacute; de col&egrave;re rend l&apos;&eacute;tat de l&apos;enfant si violent, qu&apos;on en vient &agrave; craindre les convulsions; on la calme comme on peut, on emporte la poup&eacute;e en promettant de la gu&eacute;rir, et enfin on r&eacute;ussit &agrave; endormir la petite fille, accabl&eacute;e de fatigue. Pendant son sommeil, on court chez les gens du m&eacute;tier. Un beau visage neuf est substitu&eacute; tr&egrave;s adroitement &agrave; l&apos;ancien visage, et l&apos;on s&apos;attend qu&apos;&agrave; son r&eacute;veil la jeune fille sera satisfaite; pas du tout; sa douleur, aussi vive que jamais, a pris un caract&egrave;re tendre et d&eacute;chirant. Ce n&apos;est plus une petite furie, c&apos;est une vraie m&egrave;re &agrave; laquelle on va pr&eacute;senter un autre enfant au lieu du sien. Les sanglots lui coupent la parole:&ldquo;Oh! ce n&apos;est plus, ce n&apos;est plus ma poup&eacute;e... &rdquo; <font color="green">[At this age of four, when the prestige usually begins to dissipate, a child drops his darling doll, which unfortunately breaks his nose. Terrible screams, terrible despair, which redoubles when an imprudent father, not taking the thing seriously enough, half laughing, half seeking to mend the poor face, pushes the rest of the sick nose into a huge cavity. Then a sorrow mixed with anger renders the condition of the child so violent, that one comes to fear convulsions; we calm her as best we can, we take the doll with her, promising to cure her, and finally we manage to put the little girl to sleep, overwhelmed with fatigue. During his sleep, we run to the people of the trade. A handsome new face is very adroitly substituted for the old face, and it is expected that when she wakes up the girl will be satisfied; not at all; his pain, as strong as ever, has taken on a tender and heartbreaking character. It&apos;s no longer a fury, it&apos;s a real mother to whom we will introduce another child instead of his own. Sobs cut off his words: &ldquo;Oh! it is no longer, it is no longer my doll ...&rdquo;]</font> <small> Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric Queyrat, <a name="FQLJ" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FQLJ"><cite title="source">Les Jeux des Enfants</cite></a> (1920) 122-3</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
